{"text":"Daniel, great question, the reference area is arbitrary.  It is simply convention that Sw is used.  This has roots in the fact that for some wind tunnel tests, the tail is actually removed so St doesn't contribute to the lift.  As long as you are consistent on which area is used to normalize you should be fine."}

{"text":"Patrick, great question.  In short, no, I don't believe the 3x3 has the same corrections.  You may want to check with Prof. Knowlen or Williams as they might know if there are actually any corrections being applied to the data for the 3x3 tunnel."}
{"text":"Hasan, that is great, what type of test were you conducting in the tunnel?  Did you get a chance to do any data reduction?"}

{"text":"@Kenneth Wilsey","mention":{"externalChannelId":"UCeaLqTFpc-P7Sw3LfGiOQBQ"}},{"text":" Ah, I see.  Yes, you can add 2*pi if you want the graphs to match up but really, it shouldn't matter as the only way that the yaw angle is used is as an argument to a cos or sin function which do not care if the yaw angle is wrapped around or not.  In short, you can usually use a wrapped or unwrapped version of the yaw angle is it usually doesn't matter."}
